    <item>
      <title>Pathing Issues</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=DevCorner&amp;message.id=12007#M12007</link>
      <description>Hello&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
Sorry for the late response on the ongoing pathing issues people have&#xD;
been posting about. I've been out of the office on PTO as I recovered&#xD;
from a long crunch cycle that ended only after PoR shipped and appeared&#xD;
reasonably stable. &lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
For those of you who don't know, I am the person who created the&#xD;
collision system in EQ, the 3D volumetric pathing system (also used by&#xD;
EQ2, incidentally), and was one of two people who created the pathing&#xD;
algorithm that EQ uses to direct NPCs to where they want to go. &lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
I've been aware of the warping problems that are going on, and have&#xD;
been going on for quite some time. However, as far as I know, this&#xD;
isn't anything new going on with pathing that is on live servers.&#xD;
Pathing systems haven't been touched in a while now. That said, I'm not&#xD;
denying the reports of changed behavior in old zones - I have no reason not to&#xD;
believe people who say it's happening. There's a&#xD;
possible explanation for this though, NPC movement behavior problems&#xD;
could perhaps be triggered by something else. For example, if another&#xD;
zone on the physical box lags out for some reason, a player may move&#xD;
past a threshold distance used by NPCs to just "beeline" to targets&#xD;
causing a pathsearch to occur which would further lag the server out.&#xD;
This kind of problem is known as a cascading falure, or race condition,&#xD;
and it is hard to accidentally repro in a dev environment. Something&#xD;
like this could explain why live servers are seeing problems we hadn't&#xD;
noticed during testing and would also explain why old zones, where&#xD;
nothing has changed with the data or logic, might be acting up.&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
About a month ago I became more concerned about the warping problems&#xD;
that seem to be exaggerated in PoR zones. These zones are big outdoor&#xD;
zones that use the 3D volume pathing system I created for LDoN and has&#xD;
been in use ever since, but had never been used in zones as large as&#xD;
the ones in PoR (it is an optional thing for us to use it, a number of&#xD;
large zones since LDoN use a less accurate system based on the original&#xD;
EQ pathing data we had to support when we rewrote pathing). I got the OK from my supervisor to take a hard look at the pathing&#xD;
system so we can try to find solutions to the warping problems and&#xD;
general pathing problems that aren't so obvious to players but&#xD;
ultimately result in server lag. I've spent a significant amount of&#xD;
time since then getting a better understanding of the portions of the&#xD;
pathing code that I didn't design or create myself&amp;nbsp; - which happens to&#xD;
deal with pathing failures, integrating pathing solutions/results with&#xD;
NPC AI, and dealing with failure cases when pathing is unable to&#xD;
provide a solution to the NPC trying to move. In other words, I've been looking at the stuff people are saying is broken with pathing.&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
As for what specifically I'm working on to fix this, I don't want to get into the details (it's pretty&#xD;
complicated, this would become a huge post) but I can say I'm making progress.&amp;nbsp; Nothing is final yet.&#xD;
My goal is to eliminate warping except in the most extreme&#xD;
circumstance. Warping is, ultimately, the result of a failure of the&#xD;
pathing system to find a solution within certain time constraints (this&#xD;
is the same reason the player find fails in places, btw, it just runs&#xD;
out of it's budgeted time). &lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
There's been a number of low level changes I've been experimenting&#xD;
with which help (a lot), but there are still some exaggerated cases where&#xD;
pathing failures can occur. Also, the changes can cause extra server&#xD;
load and I need to spend more time evaluating the impact of each of the&#xD;
changes to determine which ones make the most sense to apply. When I'm done this code will be sitting on Test server for a while because it does affect everything that moves at a fundimental level.&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
In the end, I think what an NPC should do when pathing fails is something we need to also consider as an independant question. I'll&#xD;
continue to try to minimize how often pathing fails in order to&#xD;
make things just go where they need to go as much as possible, but&#xD;
pathing can &amp;amp; will fail at some point and I think it may be time to&#xD;
consider alternatives to warping upon pathing failure. At the root of it is that we don't want to have an exploitable pathing system. This is&#xD;
something I will be discussing with the team once I have the&#xD;
alternatives identified along with any resulting impact to gameplay&#xD;
&amp;amp; server performance. If anyone has suggestions about what an NPC should do when pathing failed, please post &amp;amp; discuss. We've got some ideas, I'd like to hear what other people might think about it. As always, we will do what we think is the best for the game (which may be to not change things too much aside from reducing how often things warp, so don't be surprised if that's all that happens regardless of the discussion).&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
Cheers&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;</description>
      <pubDate>Thu, 16 Mar 2006 19:38:27 GMT</pubDate>
