      <title>How to play on the Test server</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=DevCorner&amp;message.id=5189#M5189</link>
      <description>If you're interested in testing new features, new content and fixes to existing bugs before it reaches the live servers we have a Test server that is open to the public. Access is open to the public, but there are a few special steps that have to be taken in order to access it and a few things you should know about before committing time on the Test server.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The Test server is pretty much the same as a normal live server, otherwise known as a 'production' or 'proddy' server, except that this is where we on the dev team and QA team actually work on a day to day basis. People play their characters, level up, do raids, all that fun stuff but there are some things about playing on Test that you should know about if you are thinking about playing there. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;* Servers are reset for patches quite often. Usually every day or two during the work week. On occasion we have to patch a few times in a single day due to severe bugs that require immediate attention. We try to patch in the PST mornings as early as possible, but sometimes it's the afternoon. On rare occasions it's during primetime PST play hours, but that doesn't really happen that often. A downside of this is that long respawn mobs are seen less often. An upside of this is that mobs that are up at server up are seen more often.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;* Once in a while, bugs occur that make the game difficult if not impossible to play. We do our best to correct these situations when they arise but it's not unheard of for people to be stuck in a bad situation longer than anyone is happy about. When we do discover this sort of thing going on, we help out with rollbacks and other things as appropriate.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;* There is no formal GM support. The people working here are Dev &amp; QA folks, and we try to help as much as possible but we can't promise in game support on this server. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;* Since we patch so often, you'll often find that a new executable and data has to be downloaded most of the time you start a game session. This is typically a couple megs of stuff to download. Goes pretty quick for broadband but slow connections can't help but deal with a bit of &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;* You get to see new stuff first.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;* You get to use /testbuff to start play at level 25.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;* Experience is 2x the normal rate of live servers. This is to help with player progression that is interrupted so often by patches.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;* The players on Test are a very nice bunch of folks. The nature of the server means a lot of the players are helpful, mature and really into EverQuest for the sheer fun of it.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;* You can often find Devs and QA online and bend their ears, if that's something you want to do. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;So if you think playing on Test might be for you, here is how you do it:&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;* Run the 'testeverquest.exe' instead of the normal 'everquest.exe'. This will download files specific to the test server which will usually replace files used by the regular production servers, so it is often a good idea to manually copy your normal EverQuest folder into a completely separate folder just for playing on Test. This way you can switch between Live and Test servers without having to patch every time you switch servers.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;* That's about it. Have fun, hope to see you there sometime.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Cheers,</description>
